Certainly! Below is a Java method that implements the recursive QuickSort algorithm to sort an array of integers. QuickSort is a divide-and-conquer algorithm. It works by selecting a 'pivot' element from the array and partitioning the other elements into two sub-arrays, according to whether they are less than or greater than the pivot. The sub-arrays are then sorted recursively.

```java
public class QuickSort {

    public static void quickSort(int[] arr, int begin, int end) {
        if (begin < end) {
            int partitionIndex = partition(arr, begin, end);

            // Recursively sort elements before
            // and after partition
            quickSort(arr, begin, partitionIndex-1);
            quickSort(arr, partitionIndex+1, end);
        }
    }

    private static int partition(int[] arr, int begin, int end) {
        int pivot = arr[end];
        int i = (begin-1);

        for (int j = begin; j < end; j++) {
            if (arr[j] <= pivot) {
                i++;

                // swap arr[i] and arr[j]
                int swapTemp = arr[i];
                arr[i] = arr[j];
                arr[j] = swapTemp;
            }
        }

        // swap arr[i+1] and arr[end] (or pivot)
        int swapTemp = arr[i+1];
        arr[i+1] = arr[end];
        arr[end] = swapTemp;

        return i+1;
    }

    // Example usage
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] inputArray = { 9, -3, 5, 2, 6, 8, -6, 1, 3 };
        quickSort(inputArray, 0, inputArray.length - 1);
        for (int i = 0; i < inputArray.length; i++) {
            System.out.print(inputArray[i] + " ");
        }
    }
}
```

This code defines a `quickSort` method that sorts the array `arr` between the indices `begin` and `end` using the QuickSort algorithm. The `partition` method is used to find the partitioning index where elements on the left are less than the pivot and elements on the right are greater. The `quickSort` method is then recursively called on the sub-arrays formed by partitioning around this index.

To create a hybrid sorting algorithm that combines QuickSort with Insertion Sort, we can modify the QuickSort implementation to use Insertion Sort for segments of the array that are smaller than a certain threshold. This approach can improve performance on small arrays. Here's how you can implement it:

```java
public class HybridQuickSort {

    private static final int THRESHOLD = 10;

    public static void hybridQuickSort(int[] arr, int begin, int end) {
        if (begin < end) {
            if (end - begin < THRESHOLD) {
                // Use Insertion Sort for small segments
                insertionSort(arr, begin, end);
            } else {
                int partitionIndex = partition(arr, begin, end);

                hybridQuickSort(arr, begin, partitionIndex - 1);
                hybridQuickSort(arr, partitionIndex + 1, end);
            }
        }
    }

    private static void insertionSort(int[] arr, int begin, int end) {
        for (int i = begin + 1; i <= end; i++) {
            int key = arr[i];
            int j = i - 1;

            while (j >= begin && arr[j] > key) {
                arr[j + 1] = arr[j];
                j = j - 1;
            }
            arr[j + 1] = key;
        }
    }

    private static int partition(int[] arr, int begin, int end) {
        int pivot = arr[end];
        int i = (begin - 1);

        for (int j = begin; j < end; j++) {
            if (arr[j] <= pivot) {
                i++;

                int swapTemp = arr[i];
                arr[i] = arr[j];
                arr[j] = swapTemp;
            }
        }

        int swapTemp = arr[i + 1];
        arr[i + 1] = arr[end];
        arr[end] = swapTemp;

        return i + 1;
    }

    // Example usage
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] inputArray = { 9, -3, 5, 2, 6, 8, -6, 1, 3 };
        hybridQuickSort(inputArray, 0, inputArray.length - 1);
        for (int i = 0; i < inputArray.length; i++) {
            System.out.print(inputArray[i] + " ");
        }
    }
}
```

In this implementation, the `hybridQuickSort` method decides whether to use QuickSort or Insertion Sort based on the size of the segment it's sorting. If the segment size is below the `THRESHOLD` (set to 10 in this example), it uses Insertion Sort; otherwise, it proceeds with the QuickSort algorithm. This hybrid approach leverages the efficiency of QuickSort for large segments and the efficiency of Insertion Sort for small segments, potentially offering better overall performance.

