Merge Sort is a divide-and-conquer algorithm that divides the input array into two halves, calls itself for the two halves, and then merges the two sorted halves. Here's a simple implementation in Java:

```java
public class MergeSort {

    // Main function that sorts arr[l..r] using merge()
    void sort(int arr[], int l, int r) {
        if (l < r) {
            // Find the middle point
            int m = (l + r) / 2;

            // Sort first and second halves
            sort(arr, l, m);
            sort(arr, m + 1, r);

            // Merge the sorted halves
            merge(arr, l, m, r);
        }
    }

    // Merges two subarrays of arr[]
    void merge(int arr[], int l, int m, int r) {
        // Find sizes of two subarrays to be merged
        int n1 = m - l + 1;
        int n2 = r - m;

        /* Create temp arrays */
        int L[] = new int[n1];
        int R[] = new int[n2];

        /*Copy data to temp arrays*/
        for (int i = 0; i < n1; ++i)
            L[i] = arr[l + i];
        for (int j = 0; j < n2; ++j)
            R[j] = arr[m + 1 + j];

        /* Merge the temp arrays */

        // Initial indexes of first and second subarrays
        int i = 0, j = 0;

        // Initial index of merged subarray array
        int k = l;
        while (i < n1 && j < n2) {
            if (L[i] <= R[j]) {
                arr[k] = L[i];
                i++;
            } else {
                arr[k] = R[j];
                j++;
            }
            k++;
        }

        /* Copy remaining elements of L[] if any */
        while (i < n1) {
            arr[k] = L[i];
            i++;
            k++;
        }

        /* Copy remaining elements of R[] if any */
        while (j < n2) {
            arr[k] = R[j];
            j++;
            k++;
        }
    }

    // Driver method
    public static void main(String args[]) {
        int arr[] = {12, 11, 13, 5, 6, 7};

        System.out.println("Given Array");
        printArray(arr);

        MergeSort ob = new MergeSort();
        ob.sort(arr, 0, arr.length - 1);

        System.out.println("\nSorted array");
        printArray(arr);
    }

    /* A utility function to print array of size n */
    static void printArray(int arr[]) {
        int n = arr.length;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i)
            System.out.print(arr[i] + " ");
        System.out.println();
    }
}
```

This code defines a `MergeSort` class with a `sort` method to recursively divide the array and a `merge` method to combine the arrays back in sorted order. The `main` method demonstrates sorting an array of integers.

To dynamically add a countdown timer to a webpage that starts from 60 seconds and updates every second until it reaches 0, you can use the following JavaScript function. This function creates a new element on the page to display the countdown, then uses `setInterval` to decrease the countdown every second, and updates the display accordingly. When the countdown reaches 0, it clears the interval to stop the countdown.

```javascript
function createCountdownTimer() {
  // Create a new div element to show the countdown
  var countdownElement = document.createElement('div');
  countdownElement.setAttribute('id', 'countdownTimer');
  countdownElement.style.fontSize = '20px'; // Example styling, customize as needed
  document.body.appendChild(countdownElement); // Append the div to the body or any specific element

  // Set the countdown start value
  var countdownValue = 60;

  // Update the countdown every second
  var countdownInterval = setInterval(function() {
    // Decrease the countdown value
    countdownValue--;

    // Update the countdown display
    countdownElement.innerText = `Countdown: ${countdownValue} seconds`;

    // Check if the countdown has reached 0
    if (countdownValue <= 0) {
      // Stop the countdown
      clearInterval(countdownInterval);
      // Optionally, display a message or perform an action when the countdown ends
      countdownElement.innerText = 'Countdown finished!';
    }
  }, 1000); // 1000 milliseconds = 1 second
}

// Call the function to start the countdown
createCountdownTimer();
```

This function can be called directly in your JavaScript code to start the countdown timer. It dynamically creates a new `div` element to display the countdown, which is updated every second. The countdown starts from 60 seconds and decreases until it reaches 0, at which point it stops and can display a final message or trigger any other action as needed.

